{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2013}}
[[File:BentoXVI-29-10052007.jpg|thumb|Pope Benedict XVI in 2007]]

The pending '''resignation of [[Pope Benedict XVI]]''' (n<U+00E9> Joseph Ratzinger) was announced on the morning of 11 February 2013, when the [[Holy See|Vatican]] confirmed that he would [[papal resignation|resign the papacy]] on 28 February at 8:00PM [[Rome]] time.<ref>{{cite news|title=Pope Benedict XVI's resignation explained|url=http://edition.cnn.com/2013/02/11/world/europe/pope-resignation-q-and-a/index.html|accessdate=18 February 2013|newspaper=[[CNN]]|date=12 February 2013|first=Susannah| last=Cullinane}}</ref><ref name=Guardian-2013-02-11>{{cite news|first1=Lizzy |last1=Davies| first2=John| last2=Hooper| first3=Kate| last3=Connelly| url=http://www.guardian.co.uk/world/2013/feb/11/pope-benedict-xvi-resigns-age |title=Pope Benedict XVI resigns due to age and declining health |publisher=Guardian Media Group |newspaper=The Guardian |date=11 February 2013 |accessdate=11 February 2013}}</ref> Benedict's decision to step down as leader of the [[Catholic Church]] will make him the first pope to relinquish the office since [[Pope Gregory XII]] in 1415<ref name="resignCNN">{{cite web | url=http://edition.cnn.com/2013/02/11/world/europe/pope-benedict-resignation/?hpt=hp_t1 | title=Pope Benedict to resign at the end of the month, Vatican says | publisher=CNN | date=11 February 2013 | accessdate=11 February 2013 | last=Messia| first=Hada}}</ref> (who did so in order to end the [[Western Schism]]), and the first to do so <!--"freely" would indicate Gregory XII wasn't free-->on his own initiative since [[Pope Celestine V]] in 1294.<ref>{{cite web|title = The Holy Father takes his leave|author = Father Raymond J. de Souza|url = http://fullcomment.nationalpost.com/2013/02/12/father-raymond-j-de-souza-on-the-pope-the-holy-father-takes-his-leave/|publisher = ''[[The National Post]]''|date = 12 February 2013| accessdate=12 February 2013}}</ref> The move was unexpected,<ref name="BBCresign1">{{cite news | url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-21411304 | title=Pope Benedict XVI in shock resignation | publisher=BBC | work= BBC News|date=11 February 2013 | accessdate=11 February 2013}}</ref> as in the [[modern history|modern era]] popes have held the position from election until death.<ref name="BBCresign1"/> The Pope stated that the reason for his decision was his declining health due to old age.<ref name="VatRadio_resign"/> [[Papal conclave, 2013|The conclave]] to select his successor will probably begin sometime between 15 March and 20 March 2013.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.catholicnewsagency.com/news/conclave-to-determine-new-pope-could-be-held-mid-march/|title=Conclave to determine new Pope could be held mid-March|publisher=Catholic News Service|date=13 February 2013}}</ref>

==Resignation address==
{{See|Papal resignation}}
Benedict decided in February 2013 that, due to his advanced age, he would resign.<ref>{{cite web|title=The future is God's| url=http://www.osservatoreromano.va/portal/dt?JSPTabContainer.setSelected=JSPTabContainer%2FDetail&last=false=&path=/news/editoriali/2013/direttore/035q13-Il-futuro--di-Dio.html&title=It%20is%20God%27s%20future&locale=en |publisher=[[L'Osservatore Romano]]|accessdate=11 February 2013|date=12 February 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=El Papa tom<U+00F3> la decisi<U+00F3>n de renunciar tras su visita a M<U+00E9>xico y Cuba|url=http://blogs.cnnmexico.com/ultimas-noticias/2013/02/11/el-papa-tomo-la-decision-de-renunciar-tras-su-visita-a-mexico-y-cuba/|accessdate=11 February 2013|newspaper=[[CNN en Espa<U+00F1>ol|CNNM<U+00E9>xico]]|date=11 February 2013|agency=[[Turner Broadcasting System]]|language=Spanish}}</ref> He will be 85 years old at the planned date of his retirement. 

He announced his intention to resign in [[Latin]] at the [[Apostolic Palace]] in the [[Sala del Concistoro]], at an early morning gathering on 11 February 2013, which was the [[World Day of the Sick]], a Vatican holy day. The gathering was to announce the date of the canonisation of three Catholic martyrs, [[Martyrs of Otranto|Antonio Primaldo and companions]], Laura Montoya Upegui, and Maria Guadalupe Garcia Zavala.<ref>{{cite web|title=Pope convokes consistory for canonization of three Blessed|url=http://www.news.va/en/news/pope-convokes-consistory-for-canonization-of-three|work=The Vatican Today |accessdate=12 February 2013|date=4 February 2013}}</ref> At the ceremony, known as the "[[Consistory]] for the canonization of the [[martyrs of Otranto]]", he told those present he had made "a decision of great importance for the life of the church".<ref name=Guardian-2013-02-11/><ref name=NBC-2013-02-11>{{cite web|url= http://worldnews.nbcnews.com/_news/2013/02/11/16924342-pope-benedict-xvi-to-resign-on-feb-28-vatican-says?lite| first1=Claudio| last1=Lavanga| first2=Erin| last2=McClam| first3=Alastair| last3=Jamieson| title=Pope Benedict XVI, citing deteriorating strength, will step aside Feb. 28| publisher=NBC News}}</ref> 

In a statement, Benedict cited his [[Pope Benedict XVI#Health|deteriorating strength due to old age]] and the physical and mental demands of the papacy.<ref name="VatRadio_resign"/> He also declared that he would continue to serve the church "through a life dedicated to prayer".<ref name="VatRadio_resign">{{cite web | url=http://en.radiovaticana.va/articolo.asp?c=663815 | title=Pope Benedict XVI announces his resignation at end of month | publisher=Vatican Radio | date=11 February 2013 | accessdate=11 February 2013}}</ref> On 17 February 2013, Pope Benedict, speaking in [[Spanish language|Spanish]], requested prayers from the crowd in front of St. Peter's Square for himself and the new pope.<ref name=NBC-2013-02-17>{{cite web|url = http://worldnews.nbcnews.com/_news/2013/02/17/16993373-pope-benedict-tells-cheering-crowd-to-pray-for-me-and-next-pope?lite=|title = Pope Benedict tells cheering crowd to pray 'for me and next pope'|publisher = NBC News}}</ref>

[[Papal conclave, 2013|The conclave]] to select his successor will probably begin sometime between 15 March and 20 March 2013.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.catholicnewsagency.com/news/conclave-to-determine-new-pope-could-be-held-mid-march/|title=Conclave to determine new Pope could be held mid-March|publisher=Catholic News Service|date=13 February 2013}}</ref>

==Post-papacy==
According to Vatican spokesman [[Federico Lombardi]], S.J., Pope Benedict XVI will not have the title of Cardinal when he retires, and will not be eligible to hold any office in the Roman Curia. <ref>{{cite web|url = http://www.catholicnews.com/data/stories/cns/1300603.htm|title = Benedict will be prayerful presence in next papacy, spokesman says|first1=Carol |last1=Glatz|first2= Cindy |last2=Wooden|publisher = Catholic News Service|date = 12 February 2013}}</ref> On February 22, Cardinal [[Francesco Coccopalmerio]], the president for the [[Pontifical Council for Legislative Texts]], stated that after the Pope's resignation his [[style (manner of address)|style]] and title will be ''[[His Holiness]] Benedict XVI, Bishop Emeritus of Rome''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.romereports.com/palio/top-ranking-cardinal-reveals-future-title-for-benedict-xvi-english-9121.html#.USeREuSpD5E|title=Top ranking cardinal reveals future title for Benedict XVI|publisher=Rome Reports TV|date=2013-02-22}}</ref>

Benedict is expected to reside in the Apostolic Palace in [[Castel Gandolfo]] immediately following his resignation. He will move permanently when renovation is finished to Vatican City's [[Mater Ecclesiae (monastery)|Mater Ecclesiae]], a monastery previously used by nuns for stays of up to several years at a time.<ref name="mater ecclesia">{{cite news |url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/news/article-2277568/Now-Popes-Rome-turmoil-claim-Benedict-stay-advise-successor-nunnery-spend-retirement-revealed.html |title=Now will there be TWO Popes? |newspaper=[[Daily Mail]] |last1=Doughty|first1=Steve|first2=Hannah|last2= Roberts |date=2013-02-12 |accessdate=2012-02-14}}</ref> According to anonymous Vatican officials, Benedict's continued presence in the Vatican City will assist with the provision of security, prevent his retirement location from becoming a place of pilgrimage and provide him with legal protection from potential lawsuits.<ref name="resignation immunity">{{cite news|url=http://www.reuters.com/article/2013/02/15/us-pope-resignation-immunity-idUSBRE91E0ZI20130215 |title=Pope will have security, immunity by remaining in the Vatican |newspaper=[[Reuters]] |date=2013-02-15|first1=Phillip|last1=Pullella}}</ref>

==Reactions==
;State
*{{flag|Canada}}&nbsp;<U+2013> Prime Minister [[Stephen Harper]] released a statement saying that Benedict "will always have a special place in the hearts of Canadians" and "[[Laureen Harper|Laureen]] and I join all Canadians in wishing Pope Benedict well in the future."<ref>{{cite web|url=http://pm.gc.ca/eng/media.asp?category=3&featureId=6&pageId=49&id=5285|title=Statement by the Prime Minister of Canada on the resignation of Pope Benedict XVI|author=Prime Minister's Office|date=11 February 2013|publisher=Prime Minister of Canada's Office|accessdate=13 February 2013}}</ref>

*{{flag|France}}&nbsp;<U+2013> President [[Fran<U+00E7>ois Hollande]] said Benedict XVI merits "respect" but did not comment on the matter specifically as it is internal to the Roman Catholic Church.<ref>{{Cite web|url = http://www.thelocal.fr/page/view/pope-benedict-merits-respect-hollande-says|title = Pope Benedict merits 'respect', Hollande says|publisher = ''The Local''}}</ref>
 	
*{{flag|Germany}}&nbsp;<U+2013> Chancellor [[Angela Merkel]] praised him as "one of the most significant religious thinkers of our time", mentioned his efforts in intercultural dialogue and said about his influence on her: "The pope's words will accompany me for a long time to come." <ref>[http://www.dw.de/germany-and-europe-hail-retiring-pope-benedict-xvi/a-16592110 Germany and Europe hail retiring Pope Benedict XVI], [[Deutsche Welle]], 11 February 2013</ref> The government's press secretary, [[Steffen Seibert]], said that he was "moved and touched," while "the German government has the highest respect for the Holy Father, for what he has done, for his contributions over the course of his life to the Catholic Church. [...] He has left a very personal signature as a thinker at the head of the Church, and also as a shepherd."<ref>{{Cite web|url = http://www.reuters.com/article/2013/02/11/pope-resigns-germany-idUSB4N09F02B20130211|title = German government "moved" by Pope Benedict's resignation|publisher = [[Reuters]]|date=11 February 2013|accessdate=14 February 2013}}</ref>
	
*{{flag|Ireland}}&nbsp;<U+2013> President [[Michael D. Higgins]] also extended his best wishes towards the resigning Pope, acknowledging his personal commitment to the [[Catholic Church]]. [[Taoiseach]] [[Enda Kenny]] praised Pope Benedict XVI's "strong leadership" and "great service to the Church" both in Ireland and throughout the world after the pontiff's resignation. <ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.irishtimes.com/newspaper/breaking/2013/0211/breaking34.html | title=Kenny pays tribute to Pope Benedict | publisher=The Irish Times | date=11 February 2013 | accessdate=12 February 2013}}</ref>
		
*{{flag|Italy}}&nbsp;<U+2013> Prime Minister [[Mario Monti]] said he was "greatly shaken by this unexpected news"<ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.usatoday.com/story/news/world/2013/02/11/pope-bendidict-germany/1908843/| title=World leaders surprised, but respect pope's decision| first=Doug| last=Stanglin| publisher=USA Today| date=February 11, 2013| accessdate=|February 18, 2013}}</ref><ref>http://www.pressconnects.com/article/20130211/APHEADS/302110027/World-reaction-Italian-PM-greatly-shaken-by-decision?nclick_check=1</ref><ref>http://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/europe/benedict-xvi-the-revolutionary-pope-resignation-seen-as-eruption-of-modernity-8490481.html</ref><ref>http://www.breakingnews.com/item/ahZzfmJyZWFraW5nbmV3cy13d3ctaHJkcg0LEgRTZWVkGITb9AwM/2013/02/11/italys-prime-minister-monti-says-he-is-greatly-shaken-by-the-news-of</ref><ref>http://www.poughkeepsiejournal.com/article/20130211/NEWS/130211008/World-reaction-Italian-PM-greatly-shaken-by-decision?nclick_check=1</ref><ref>http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-21409149</ref><ref>http://www.nydailynews.com/news/world/worlwide-leaders-react-pope-benedict-xvi-resignation-article-1.1260726?localLinksEnabled=false</ref>

*{{flag|Philippines}}&nbsp;<U+2013> President [[Benigno Aquino III]] was "filled with great regret as news comes of Pope Benedict XVI announcing he intends to relinquish the Petrine Ministry on {{As written|February 28}} of this year." He also recalled the "fond gratitude, the many prayers and comforting words Pope Benedict XVI has dedicated to Filipinos in times of calamity and challenge, and his words of encouragement and witness in the many Catholic events that have brought Catholics together, such as the recent canonisation of [[Pedro Calungsod|San Pedro Calungsod]]."<ref>[http://www.gov.ph/2013/02/11/statement-the-presidential-spokesperson-on-the-popes-resignation-february-11-2013 Statement of The Presidential Spokesperson on the Pope<U+2019>s resignation]</ref>
	
*{{flag|United Kingdom}}&nbsp;<U+2013> Prime Minister [[David Cameron]] praised Benedict XVI, saying: "I send my best wishes to Pope Benedict following his announcement today. He has worked tirelessly to strengthen [[Holy See<U+2013>United Kingdom relations|Britain's relations with the Holy See]]. His [[Pope Benedict XVI's visit to the United Kingdom|visit to Britain in 2010]] is remembered with great respect and affection." He added that "He will be missed as a spiritual leader to millions."<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.number10.gov.uk/news/resignation-of-pope-benedict/ |title=Statement from Prime Minister David Cameron following the resignation of Pope Benedict XVI |date=11 February 2013 |work= |publisher=[[10 Downing Street]] |accessdate=12 February 2013}}</ref>
	
*{{flag|United States of America}}&nbsp;<U+2013> President [[Barack Obama]] praised Benedict XVI, saying: "On behalf of Americans everywhere, [[Michelle Obama|Michelle]] and I wish to extend our appreciation and prayers to His Holiness Pope Benedict XVI. Michelle and I warmly remember our meeting with the Holy Father in 2009, and I have appreciated our work together over these last four years."<ref name="guard"/> He added that he wished "the best to those who will soon gather to choose His Holiness Pope Benedict XVI's successor."<ref name="abcnews">[http://abcnews.go.com/International/pope-benedict-xvi-resigns-president-obama-italian-prime/story?id=18465356 Pope Benedict XVI Resigns: President Obama, Italian Prime Minister, Other World and Church Leaders React]</ref> 

;Religious
U.S. [[Timothy M. Dolan|Cardinal Timothy Dolan]] said that he "brought a listening heart to victims of sexual abuse".<ref name="guard">[http://www.guardian.co.uk/world/2013/feb/11/pope-benedict-selfless-leadership-us-church Pope Benedict's 'selfless leadership' praised by US church leaders&nbsp;<U+2013> President pays tribute to pope's work while senior Catholics say Benedict 'brought a listening heart to victims of sexual abuse'], [[The Guardian]], 11 February 2013</ref><ref name="abcnews"/>

[[Ashkenazi]] Chief Rabbi [[Yona Metzger]]'s spokesman said: "During his period there were the best relations ever between the church and the chief rabbinate and we hope that this trend will continue. I think he deserves a lot of credit for advancing inter-religious links the world over between [[Pope Benedict XVI and Judaism|Judaism]], Christianity and [[Pope Benedict XVI and Islam|Islam]]." The spokesman also said that Metzger wished Benedict XVI "good health and long days."<ref>{{Cite web|url = http://www.jpost.com/International/Article.aspx?id=302877|title = As pope steps down, chief rabbi lauds Vatican ties|publisher = ''[[The Jerusalem Post]]''}}</ref>

==Events surrounding his last hours as pope==
Benedict XVI will appear for the last time in public during his regular Wednesday audience of 27 February 2013.<ref>{{Cite web|url = http://www.zenit.org/en/articles/some-faq-s-on-the-pope-s-resignation|title = Some FAQ's on the Pope's Resignation|publisher = [[Zenit News Agency]]|date = 20 February 2013|accessdate = 22 February 2013}}</ref> As of 16 February, 35,000 had already registered to attend this audience.<ref>{{Cite web|url = http://www.news.va/en/news/thousands-flocking-to-rome-to-bid-benedict-xvi-far|title = Thousands flocking to Rome to bid Benedict XVI farewell on Feb. 27th|publisher = [[news.va]]|date = 16 February 2013|accessdate = 22 February 2013}}</ref> The evening of 27 February, there will be a candlelight vigil to show support for Pope Benedict at St. Peter's Square.<ref>{{Cite web|url = http://www.culturacattolica.it/default.asp?id=17&id_n=32454#.USeYPh2zegT|title = Appello: Luce e silenzio per il Papa (Appeal: Candlelight and Silence for the Pope)|publisher = culturacattolica.it|date = 13 February 2013|accessdate = 22 February 2013}}, [http://wdtprs.com/blog/2013/02/solidarity-with-an-initiative-in-rome-of-support-for-benedict-xvi-on-27-feb/ Partial English Translation on a Blog]<!--alone such a blog would not be a reliable source--></ref>

